<section class="story" aria-labelledby="story-heading">
  <h2 id="story-heading">Why Maester exists</h2>
  <p>
    Most teams' documentation lives in too many places at once. Service
    READMEs, library wikis, internal handbooks, design docs scattered across
    private repos, and the inevitable "where is that one diagram again?"
    Slack thread. Each source has its own owner, its own review cadence,
    and its own definition of "current."
  </p>
  <p>
    Maester is a thin tool for a focused problem: let each source declare
    what it's willing to publish, and let a central aggregator pull those
    pieces into one structured tree that humans and AI agents can read.
    Source repos keep their ownership. Citadels get their reading view.
    Nobody has to migrate a CMS.
  </p>
  <p>
    The project started from the observation that AI coding agents perform
    measurably better when they can ground their context against a single,
    well-structured documentation surface — and that the same surface
    happens to make life easier for the humans they assist.
  </p>
</section>

